Climatic Offences retarded economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez in the government, rose in Sinaloa unemployment and undeclared work, while the foreign investment and the economy stagnated.
2011 will remain in economic history Sinaloas. It is the first year, Mario Lopez Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of change and great hopes on the economic growth in the government, but as a result of the climatic adversity can be no question of growth, on the contrary, the most important economic indicators.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of euros in losses in agriculture, but also the growth of the state economy close borders and caused a general decline in economic activity in the first quarter of the year at 3.6 percent This is mainly on the historic 31.16% reduction in agricultural development at 31.16, which had a hindrance to further economic sectors.
According to the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable Mexican Council for sustainable agricultural development) report on the impact of the Frosts were damaged 582 000 hectares of agricultural land, of which 78.03 percent and the remaining 21.07% partially destroyed. Affected mainly of vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity until November has increased in the Mexican state unemployment. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed in the first quarter of a rapid rise in unemployment, because from January to March had 55 053 inhabitants Sinaloas no employment, which is 4.53 percent of the workforce, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% in the second quarter and from July to September to 6.19 percent, as a result, 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, 18 969 more people than in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the School of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented on the policy of public institutions declare indirectly the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing is a rise in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts by the legislation, which was adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because those who stashed accumulate dollars, it is not easy for this to work, to invest or to use it for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the idea of growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people in the country to search for work abroad, especially in the United States, left, has decreased. That is due to visa problems and on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work. These people remain here and looking for work, with unemployment," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, given the high proportion of undeclared work under INEGI 60.38% of the country's employees, who work without pay into the of the social insurance.
The unemployment and undeclared work, the low wages, the lowest throughout Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo Previsión y Social (governmental authority for labour and Social welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa, until September 5352 pesos; it is much less than the federal average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to reducing economic activity and rising unemployment will in 2011, the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years, according to Secretaría de Economía (state economic authority), FDI from January to June 630 597, a decline of 87.74% compared to the 5 143$312 over the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (governmental authority for economic development) recorded a total investment of EUR 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, which comes mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis the country's government in July in the National Congress a loan of EUR 3 000 000 000 pesos, which should be invested to reactivate the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, the country's Congress approved a sum of EUR 200 600 000 pesos, however, be found by November no positive effects of debt of any of the industries in the country.
Reactions
For the representatives of the business was the first year of government Mario López Valdés government incompetence.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the chamber of Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (state of manufacturing in Mexico) that in 2011 no efforts to harmonize the views of the various sectors, including the country's government, has been made.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa this year was very poor. It needs to be worked hard to regain the lost ground this year and 2012, we need to double the efforts of all and in particular the progress of the already well matched eingestimmte government teams have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year, the country's economic development and growth slowed.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the Frosts. One of the most important impact is a slower economy, which is not enough to create an economic dynamism, which could create a reasonable flow of processes, products and services, which is why we will conclude the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of Andalusia Patronal de la República Mexicana employers" association (Mexico) said in Sinaloa, we need to get the state to more productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that worked, and we believe that it is necessary to redefine a long-term programme to develop the country's economic appeal and line because it is important to activate all the material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There is much to be done
The chairman of Coparmex stressed how important it is to develop a vision of the future, the government's efforts to better track.
"In general, I would say that the government has made in various areas of good results. Economic development has come forward, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power have made progress in the government.
"There are areas in which we can say that the government has taken. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is a great deal of work lies ahead of it," he said.
